0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiteracy Practices in Transition explores the connections between local, situated literacy practices and global processes of mobility in the geographical space of the Nordic countries, an example of contemporary mobile societies. The detailed empirical analyses show how these connections affect individuals, practices and policies; how the global and local meet in discourses and practices and how people need to (re)negotiate their way in the complex and messy spaces in which they move. The volume challenges current trends in the global standardization of language and literacy education. Instead, it promotes the idea of literacy as a multiple, multilingual, multimodal and constantly contestable and negotiable phenomenon, which calls for the development of language and literacy education that is sensitive to the needs and experiences of the individual actors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEducationzScandinavia. 0aLiteracyzScandinavia. 0aMultilingualismzScandinavia. 0aScandinavian studentszEurope. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Literacy.2bisacsh  aNordic countries.  aglobalisation.  alanguage and education.  alanguage and society.  alanguage policy.  aliteracy practices.  amobility.1 aAxelsson, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagga-Gupta, Sangeeta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarton, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanbolt, Anne Marit Vesteraas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDanielsson, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaugaard, Line Møller, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov